-- PRESS DIGEST- Financial Times - June 13
-- 
-- Thu Jun 12, 2014 08:53PM EDT
-- None



June 13 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  BNP TOP EXECUTIVE CHODRON DE COURCEL TO RETIRE AMID U.S. PROBE (http://link.reuters.com/dew99v)  RETURN OF CORPORATE PC DEMAND BOOSTS INTEL (http://link.reuters.com/bew99v)  TWITTER PARTS WAYS WITH CHIEF OPERATING OFFICER (http://link.reuters.com/few99v)  TESLA MOTORS OPENS DOOR TO ELECTRIC VEHICLES' TECHNOLOGY SECRETS (http://link.reuters.com/cew99v)  FRANCE DELIBERATES AFTER SIEMENS CHANGES TACK IN ALSTOM BID (http://link.reuters.com/gew99v)  Overview  Georges Chodron de Courcel, one of the most senior figures at BNP Paribas <BNPP.PA>, has announced his retirement amid an escalating probe by U.S regulators in alleged sanctions violations at the French bank.  Strong demand for business PCs drove U.S. chipmaker Intel <INTC.O> to raise its second-quarter profit guidance, pushing shares up by more than 5 percent in after-hours trading.  Twitter's <TWTR.N> Chief Operating Officer Ali Rowghani has stepped down following a boardroom disagreement, as he pushed for the company to make a large acquisition of a music company to get more users, according to people familiar with the matter.  U.S. electric carmaker Tesla Motors <TSLA.O> has made an  unexpected move in revealing its technology secrets to its rivals as Chief Executive Elon Musk aims to boost interest in the low-emission vehicles.